===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|sake|t=sake, cause}}, from {{inh|en|ang|sacu|t=cause, lawsuit, legal action, complaint, issue, dispute}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*sakō|t=affair, thing, charge, accusation, matter}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*seh₂g-|t=to investigate}}. Akin to {{cog|fy|saak|t=cause; business}}, {{cog|nds|Saak}}, {{cog|nl|zaak|t=matter; cause; business}}, {{cog|de|Sache|t=thing; matter; cause; legal cause}}, {{cog|da|sag}}, {{cog|sv|-}} and {{cog|no|sak}}, {{cog|got|𐍃𐌰𐌺𐌾𐍉|t=dispute, argument}}, {{cog|ang|sōcn||inquiry, prosecution}}, {{cog|ang|sēcan|t=to seek}}. More at [[soke]], [[soken]], [[seek]].

====Pronunciation====
* {{enPR|sāk}}, {{IPA|en|/seɪk/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-sake.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|eɪk}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# [[cause]], [[interest]] or [[account]]
#: {{ux|en|For the '''sake''' of argument}}
# [[purpose]] or [[end]]; [[reason]]
#: {{ux|en|For old times' '''sake'''}}
# the benefit or regard of someone or something
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1897|author=[[w:Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill]]| title={{w|The Celebrity}}| chapter=1| url=http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2341853W| passage=When I gave a dinner there was generally a cover laid for him. I liked the man for his own '''sake''', and even had he promised to turn out a celebrity it would have had no weight with me.}}
#* '''2005''', {{w|Plato}}, ''Sophist''. Translation by Lesley Brown. [[w:Stephanus pagination|242a-b]].
#*: But it will be for your '''sake''' that we'll undertake to refute this thesis,{{...}}
# {{qualifier|obsolete except in phrases}} [[contention]], [[strife]]; [[guilt]], [[sin]], [[accusation]] or charge
#* ''Genesis'', 3:17
#*: And unto Adam He said, Because thou hast hearkened unto the voice of thy wife, and hast eaten of the tree, of which I commanded thee, saying, Thou shalt not eat of it: cursed is the ground for thy '''sake'''; in sorrow shalt thou eat of it all the days of thy life.

=====Usage notes=====
* The word ''sake'' is generally used in constructions of the form "for X's sake" or "for the sake of X", where X is a noun (see the quotations above, [[for sake of]], and [[for the sake of]]).

* Garner's ''Modern American Usage'' notes it is common to write an apostrophe rather than apostrophe–ess in this construction when the noun ends in an /s/ or /z/ sound: ''[[for appearance' sake]], [[for goodness' sake]]''.

